	<div id="content" class="hfeed">
	<article class="post-1577 post type-post status-publish hentry tag-after-deadline tag-grammar" id="post-1577">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">The Great Dangler Debate</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Philip B. Corbett			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2015-09-08T12:00:42+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">September 8, 2015 8:00 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">September 8, 2015 8:00 am</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//afterdeadline.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/09/08/the-great-dangler-debate/" data-title="The Great Dangler Debate" data-description="Some danglers are harmless, but others create a slipshod, unpolished quality in our prose. Here are a few recent cases where our vigilance slipped.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">How bad are danglers, really?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">No less an authority than <a href="//stevenpinker.com/">Steven Pinker</a> argues that the vehement opposition of many traditionalists is often unwarranted. Many constructions that are technically danglers, <a href="//www.theguardian.com/books/2014/aug/15/steven-pinker-10-grammar-rules-break">he has written</a>, are perfectly clear, idiomatic and acceptable. Writers and editors should be concerned only about a subset of danglers that create real awkwardness or potential confusion.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">(A reminder for those who skipped <a href="//www.amazon.com/Miss-Thistlebottoms-Hobgoblins-Bugbears-Outmoded/dp/0374523150/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&#038;qid=1441314266&#038;sr=8-1&#038;keywords=miss+thistlebottom%27s+hobgoblins">Miss Thistlebottom&#8217;s class</a>: Danglers are modifiers &mdash; including participle phrases, &#8220;like&#8221; comparisons and appositives &mdash; that are not adjacent to the noun or pronoun they refer to. They are said to &#8220;dangle&#8221; without a clear connection to what they describe.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I know better than to quarrel with Professor Pinker, an elegant writer and thinker whose understanding of grammar is deeper than any pixel-stained journalist&#8217;s. He is certainly right that some danglers are harmless and will go unnoticed by all but the most persnickety readers. But our prose is often written and edited very quickly, and danglers can expose that haste, creating a slipshod, unpolished quality. Many readers, too, are in a hurry, and we should strive to smooth their path to prevent stumbles. And as Professor Pinker himself notes, some readers who are particularly averse to danglers will judge a writer harshly for any perceived lapse. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;So in formal styles,&#8221; he concludes, &#8220;it&#8217;s not a bad idea to keep an eye open for them and to correct the obtrusive ones.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I agree. Here are a few recent cases where our vigilance slipped:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>After operating under cover for most of his career, his public profile</strong> rose with his retirement.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A classic dangling participle &mdash; &#8220;his public profile&#8221; did not operate under cover. Granted, readers will understand what we meant. But the sentence is awkward, and could easily be recast without the dangler.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>They kept each other at bay until the next day, when, <strong>after returning home from brunch at the Noho Star, their resistance</strong> melted.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Here, too, the meaning is clear enough. But &#8220;their resistance&#8221; did not return home from brunch. Why annoy the purists unnecessarily? We could easily fix the dangler. One solution: &#8220;after they returned home &hellip;&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>A native of Turkey, coffee in his mind was thick and sweet,</strong> brewed in a copper pot lined with silver called a cezve and served in tiny, delicate glasses. American coffee, he said, made his stomach hurt.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This dangling appositive is particularly jarring. A reader expects &#8220;a native of Turkey&#8221; to be followed by &#8220;he&#8221; or &#8220;Mr. Ulukaya.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Mr. Redd said that <strong>his dreams were often violent but that they became that way only after coming to Pelican Bay.</strong></em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">With this construction, &#8220;after coming to Pelican Bay&#8221; seems to refer to the dreams, rather than to Mr. Redd. A simple fix: &#8220;only after he came to &hellip;&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>The lone survivor of the core four, Ani&#8217;s healing</strong> began a couple episodes ago when she recalled the man who kidnapped her all those years ago.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Again, a dangling appositive phrase like this is jarring and makes the reader stumble; the reference is to Ani, not to &#8220;Ani&#8217;s healing.&#8221; One possible fix: &#8220;The lone survivor of the core four, Ani began to heal &hellip;&#8221; (Also, note that we need &#8220;of&#8221; after &#8220;couple.&#8221;)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&nbsp;<br />
<strong>In a Word</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This week&#8217;s grab bag of grammar, style and other missteps, compiled with help from colleagues and readers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>HONG KONG</strong> &mdash; Yahoo&#8217;s chief executive, Marissa Mayer, and her husband, Zachary Bogue, are expecting twin daughters, according to an announcement she made on Yahoo&#8217;s Tumblr.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Times&#8217;s reporter was in Hong Kong, but Ms. Mayer was not, and this story could have been written anywhere. When the dateline has no relevance or might mislead readers, remove it (we later did).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>For more than two decades,</strong> Mrs. Weill <strong>has been actively involved</strong> in the college&#8217;s development and governance, and <strong>has served</strong> on the board for 19 years.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Constructed this way, the phrase &#8220;for more than two decades&#8221; should apply to both parts of the predicate, &#8220;has been involved&#8221; and &#8220;has served.&#8221; That&#8217;s not what we meant. We can fix the problem by adding &#8220;she&#8221; as a separate subject for &#8220;has served,&#8221; making that part a separate clause.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Residents say that <strong>hundreds of boats leave throughout the night, and are intercepted</strong> only once citizens alert the authorities.</em> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A similar problem. As written, without a subject for the verb after &#8220;and,&#8221; the sentence suggests that &#8220;hundreds of boats &hellip; are intercepted,&#8221; which is not what we meant. Rephrase.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Mrs. Clinton said she was &#8220;deeply honored&#8221; by Mr. Harkin&#8217;s support. He stayed neutral in <strong>the 2008 Democratic presidential primary.</strong></em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It&#8217;s clearer to use &#8220;primary&#8221; to refer to single contest in a single state (though, of course, some states hold caucuses instead). For the entire nominating contest, say &#8220;primary campaign&#8221; or &#8220;primaries.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Disgusted by Mr. Trump&#8217;s assertion that Mexican immigrants are rapists and criminals, <strong>a group</strong> from the public school has started a push to have <strong>their senior prom</strong> relocated from his nearby Trump National Golf Club, the white-glove catering place in Briarcliff Manor, N.Y. &mdash; about seven miles west of Chappaqua &mdash; where it has been held for the last several years.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The plural &#8220;their&#8221; doesn&#8217;t agree with the singular &#8220;group.&#8221; We could just say &#8220;the senior prom.&#8221; (This overstuffed sentence could also use some trimming.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>He said he has tried</strong> more than a dozen times to obtain permission to cross Israel and enter the West Bank, without luck.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Sequence-of-tense rules require &#8220;He said he had tried.&#8221; (That is even more necessary here since the story reports that he had finally been permitted to make the crossing in question.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>[Capsule summary] Dominic Lieven&#8217;s new book, &#8220;The End of Tsarist Russia: The March to World War I &amp; Revolution,&#8221; looks to place Russia &#8220;where it belongs, at the very center&#8221; of the first world war, and how <strong>it&#8217;s</strong> part in that conflict resonates even in the modern era.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Its,&#8221; of course. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>In the Morgan building a valuable laylight &mdash; a skylight that <strong>lays</strong> flat &mdash; was disassembled piece by piece, restored and reinstalled.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;lies.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Gabriel GarcÃ­a-MÃ¡rquez, once asked <strong>whom</strong> the best reader of &#8220;One Hundred Years of Solitude&#8221; was, responded with a story: &#8220;A Russian friend met a lady, a very old lady, who was copying the whole book out by hand, right to the last line. &#8230; &#8220;</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Make it &#8220;who,&#8221; the subject of &#8220;was.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Ms. Burton said the company is merely trying to ensure that any portrayal of Ms. Brown, <strong>whom</strong> she fears is often reduced to clichÃ©s of being a sexually adventurous man-pleaser, shows the full range of her character and accomplishments.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">And again. Make it &#8220;who,&#8221; the subject of &#8220;is reduced.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>In August, Delaware enacted a law that <strong>forbids online school services from</strong> selling students&#8217; personal details &mdash; including their political or religious affiliations, food purchases, text messages, photos, videos and web searches &mdash; or using the information to market to them.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Times&#8217;s stylebook says this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>forbid, prohibit.</strong> Use <em>to</em> with <em>forbid</em> and <em>from</em> with <em>prohibit</em>: <em>forbid them to attend</em>; <em>prohibit them from attending</em>.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Not that anyone in Calvario much cares for &mdash; or even <strong>knows &mdash; of</strong> the broader debate over the drug trade.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The &#8220;of&#8221; goes with &#8220;knows&#8221; and should be inside the dashes.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>In places, the <strong>cement</strong> walls next to the tracks are crumbling, exposing the electrical wiring that helps power and control the system.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A reminder from the stylebook:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>cement.</strong> Use <em>concrete</em> instead to mean the material that forms blocks, walls and roads. One ingredient is <em>cement</em>, the binding agent that is mixed with water, sand and gravel.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Thus, Jeb Bush says that the retirement age should be pushed back to &#8220;68 or <strong>70&#8243;.</strong></em> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In American style, the period should come inside the close-quote mark.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>A senior judge on the United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit who was appointed to the bench by Ronald Reagan and promoted by Bill Clinton, <strong>Ms. Barry</strong>, 78, would perhaps be the ideal person to argue in her brother&#8217;s defense as he faces familiar accusations of misogyny, if she would speak publicly.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The stylebook says this:</p>
<blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Judge</strong> <em>Tracy T. Anyell</em>; <em>Judge Anyell</em>; <em>the judge</em>. Do not use <em>Mr.</em>, <em>Mrs.</em>, <em>Miss</em>, <em>Ms.</em>, etc., in later references.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>[Home page summary] A survey found a stark divide <strong>among</strong> black and white residents over the local economy, the state of schools and the quality of life 10 years after Hurricane Katrina.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The division separates the two groups, so make it &#8220;between.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Undecided Democrats said they <strong>have been pouring</strong> over the deal as they decide whether to thwart the resolution by filibuster.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We meant &#8220;poring,&#8221; not &#8220;pouring&#8221; (that was fixed for print). And sequence-of-tense rules call for &#8220;had been poring&#8221; after the past-tense &#8220;said.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em><strong>The assault was described as a terrorist attack by the Belgian prime minister</strong>, and French officials said one of the Americans was among the wounded.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Watch where you put those prepositional phrases! (Fixed in time for print.)</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>But the ranks of undecided Democrats are still full of quirks and wild cards, from a freshman senator from Michigan whose closest aide has a pro-Israeli government bent to lawmakers inclined toward avoiding military conflict but from states where any position in support of President Obama is toxic.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This long and convoluted sentence is very hard to follow.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Rights activists who monitor the treatment of refugees say while they are seeing an increase in hate crimes across Europe, particularly targeting Roma or asylum-seekers from Europe&#8217;s poorest countries, nowhere have they seen mass demonstrations or the kinds of arson attacks and other vandalism at housing for refugees like those in Germany.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another overstuffed, hard-to-read sentence. A &#8220;that&#8221; after &#8220;say&#8221; would help a little; trimming the sentence or breaking it up would help more.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>And so on Thursday, as this southwest Georgia city of fewer than 800 people absorbed the announcement that former President Jimmy Carter <strong>had received a diagnosis of cancer</strong> that had spread, the news was not just that a former president was ill.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The stylebook urges us not to say that a person was &#8220;diagnosed&#8221; with an illness (the illness is diagnosed). But in avoiding that misstep, we often resort to this wordy and unnatural expression. Why not just say Carter has cancer, or learned he had cancer?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>The Arlington police <strong>had went</strong> to the Classic Buick GMC dealership Friday just after 1 a.m. when a caller reported that a man was standing on top of a car in the lot &#8220;stamping on the windshield trying to break it,&#8221; according to a 911 call.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Several readers noticed this lapse; we meant &#8220;had gone,&#8221; of course.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>This is an asset among some moderates in New Hampshire as <strong>he presents like</strong> a pre-Tea Party Republican.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Let&#8217;s resist this faddish intransitive use of &#8220;present.&#8221; Make it &#8220;presents himself as,&#8221; or some such.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>It stopped the <strong>hemorrhaging</strong> of perspective that can occur when your <strong>caldron of competition is a fishbowl.</strong></em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Unmix that metaphor.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&bull;&bull;&bull;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Hillary Rodham Clinton is readying a $350 billion plan to address America&#8217;s student loan debt <strong>crisis,</strong> but to her Republican rivals the idea sounded like something familiar: a tax hike.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Let&#8217;s be wary of labeling this issue a &#8220;crisis&#8221; in our own words; it smacks of hyperbole. (Also, tax &#8220;increase&#8221; is preferable to &#8220;hike.&#8221;)</p>
	</div>
